
(The Chinese characters in this picture are the name of each province in China.)

(In Jupyter Notebook, this graph is dynamic based on the day at which you run this code. For this graph, it is based on 2021.12.1)

This graph depicted the contour of all the provinces of China and then saturated the area of the provinces to show the number of the accumulative cases of all the provinces. When the accumulative number of the cases for a province is bigger, the color of the area of the provinces turns darker. 


There are some good points and bad points in this picture.

Good points:

1.	Highlight the key points of data by color, and improve the efficiency of obtaining target information by reducing the need of working memory. Users who read this picture are mainly concerned about the severity of the epidemic situation in their own area.  This graph saves the process of data acquisition and analysis in the human brain, and enables people to obtain the information faster and more conveniently.

2.	The data of each province is directly shown on the map by geographic location, which more intuitively shows the distribution of the epidemic in the country. And use more attractive color shades to replace specific epidemic data, which makes the pictures more beautiful while attracting users to focus on key information.

Bad points:

There are also two vital deficiencies. 

1. To know whether a place is safe or not, we should pay attention to the current data, not the accumulative data. For example, as the source of covid-19, Wuhan province is the darkest, having most accumulative cases. However, for now, Wuhan province is much safer than a lot of provinces in China because the pandemics of Wuhan provinces has been cured at all. 

2. The principle of the graph making is based on the province contour, saturating the provinces. However, as a way that ignores the discrepancy within a province and pays more attention to the total number not the density, this principle is totally unscientific and misleading, especially for China, whose provinces are of all kinds of shape and size. 

Let me give you some examples to illustrate deficiency 2.

The deficiency of paying attention to only the total number,but not the density.
For this picture, assume that we have province A and B and the covid-19 cases are evenly distributed across the whole rectangle. Using the principles of drawing the original graph, province A seems much more dangerous than province B because it has more area and darker color. However, the truth is that everywhere in this whole rectangle is equally dangerous.

The deficiency that come from the shape of provinces.
Assume that we have province A and B. What is more, province A has city A1, A2 and A3. 
One day, there is a break out of covid-19 in city A3. Because most part of province B is around the source of covid-19, though the color of it will be shallow, it is still dangerous.


 

--Our own graph:

In this way we solved the 2 problems mentioned above, because 
1. We use the data in 2021.11.20, more convincing and immediate data than the accumulative data.
2. When we draw, we dont use the province borders at all, just adding the dots. The province borders in this new graph are just used to locate for the readers. As a result, we dont eliminate the discrepancies within a province and pay attention to both the total number and the density. 
For example, people can see how the cases are distributed within a province. What is more, a place that is dense with the red dots means that the place is very dangerous and has a high density of covid-19.

What is more, to show the cases, we use the number and positions of the dots, rather than the darkness of the color. In our storytelling class, it is said that people are more sensible with positions than with color.

--Take-home messages:

1. China is relatively safe for now. Even for 11.20, a relatively serious day for China, there are only 10 more cases in China. However, in the original graph, China looks very dangerous because it uses the accumulative number.
2. The distribution of covid-19 is very uneven, no matter for which province, there is at most one source of covid-19. As a result, even though we are in a province where there are some cases of covid-19, as long as we are not in source city, we are safe. However, in the original graph, because that we don't know the distribution within a province, what we can do is to avoid the provinces with covid-19.


--Conclusions and enlightment:

When we are making information visualization, we should consider whether our drawing principle concords with the reality. In the case for our project, the fact is that--if you are more close to covid-19 cases, then you are more dangerous. In contrast, the fact is not that--if you are in the same province with a covid-19 case, then you are definitely more dangerous. In some cases that you are in the  province with covid-19 cases but away from them because of the size of your province, you are relatively safe. All in all, what makes the original graph unreasonable and our graph reasonable is that-- our plot principle is based on reality while the original graph is not. 

In the future, whenever we need to make some data visualization, we should first have a clear understanding of the reality, device a plot principle based on the reality and then check whether our plot agrees with the reality. If not, totally get rid of our work!

However, I have to admit that there is some value for the original graph. If we draw a global graph to show which country is more dangerous  and which country is safe, we can take the original plot principle. The reason is that, the circumstance of dealing with covid-19 varies a lot from country to country. For example, China have a more powerful government to effectively implement the policy to deal with covid-19, while American government policy is sometimes harassed by some of American people. In this case, it is reasonable to draw the graph by the country border because the fact that I mentioned above agrees with the plot principle. 

All in all, always make sure that these two things agree with each other:

Reality, plot principle.
